What a weekend in Daytona…! We had some ups and downs to say the least but one thing I can say is the team and I never gave in and never gave up. @tobcracing & @triumphamerica had my back and gave me 100% the whole time!! 

As for the speeding penalty, completely my fault. I tried to anticipate the lag in pressing the limiter button and it happened to shut off just about instantly causing me to be just over the pitlane limit in 1 of the 9 sectors. 

We played our strategy well, finishing 3rd at the red flag and crossing the line 2nd in the 10 lap race. 

Big thank you to @67shakey for coming over and mentoring me throughout the weekend and having such a positive impact on our weekend!

Congrats @campetersen45 on another Daytona podium 🤘🏽 also to @joshhayes4 for riding an almost perfect race again… 

Also a massive thank you to @wearehonos , @geoscapesolar and “if you don’t know Jack?!” For coming on board for the 200. Then the long term guys, @araiamericas , @spidi_on_track, @evolvegttrackdays , @luxestarvip , @slgrafics , @pirellimotousa , @trackside_partsclub & @cccmanhattan for all the support. 

I’m excited for getting our season underway next month. 👊🏽
📸 @klings.media

As a lot of you know I unfortunately had an incident yesterday training on my Moto bike resulting in a broken L3 vertebrae in my back. 

I spent the night here in the hospital last night, waiting to find out if I’ll need surgery or not. The good news is it looks like we won’t need a surgery and they finally have me sitting up in a chair and have me trying to start walking with a walker. 

Thank you so much to everyone that took a minute out of their day to reach out to me, I really appreciate all the love and support! I am fully focused on my recovery and need to take this one very serious. 

I’ll keep y’all up to date as I learn what’s going on… ❤️🙌🏽

My 3rd weekend on the @team_hammer_inc @suzukicycles superbike is done and dusted!! It’s been so gnarly learning from the sbk boys and I think we’re making a lot of progress with my style, and the bike. I made a lot of small mistakes this weekend, but that’s part of the learning curve! Walking out with a P9, P6 and a DNF (mechanical). I’ve got some ideas on certain things to work on for the next one so we will continue to grind it out and keep getting closer to them front boys. Thanks a million to the whole team for believing in me and pushing me to become a better rider and athlete. Thanks also to @visionwheel and @missionfoodsus for making it all possible! 
📸 @brianjnelsonphoto 
#superbike #suzuki #gsxr1000r

Well… the 2023 season has come to an end. The highs and lows of this season was unbelievable. From nearly winning another 200 to breaking my back to becoming a factory Superbike rider and snagging a couple top 5s in the Motoamerica Superbike Class. 

I can’t thank the whole Vision Wheel, M4 Ecstar Suzuki team enough for taking the risk on me and bringing me onboard despite a massive injury! Team Hammer, John and Chris have been working with me on and off for a long time now and I’m so glad we could make this happen! It’s been the best couple months of my life Jumping into SBK class and working with my new crew, Ben Fox, Chris, Ray, Johnny and Ashley. 

There’s so many people to thank for getting me to the point of jumping on a Superbike! All the years of grinding on the little bikes then jumping in Supersport, Stock 1000, Motogp Moto3, FIM CEV moto3&2. A few of those people are Paulie, Mom and Andy. Classic Car Club of Manhattan, Scott at Luxestar VIP, Mark, Billy and Alex at EvolveGT, Justin at the Trackside Parts Club, Team Promotion, Arai Helmets, Spidi, XPD Boots, RST, HONOS, Billy, Ian and everyone else that has helped me and is currently helping. 

Special shout out to my manager Shane at Sixtyseven sports management!!

I can’t wait to see what 2024 brings! Much love, BP!✌🏽

2023 absolutely beat me into the ground and made me have to dig pretty deep to pull myself back up. It made me realize how much I love racing motorcycles and pushing myself to the limit. 

From a silly penalty at Daytona taking us off the podium (still sorry to the TOBC team for being trigger happy!) to a broken back within 2 weeks. To then bouncing back thanks to the Rodio Racing team, Philip Bailey and Ryne Snooks and leading the 100th Loudon classic, my first race back and ending 4th after another strange call on all the red flags. 

After Loudon my luck started to take a turn for the better though, I got a call from JU and CU from Team Hammer and they were wondering if I wanted to ride a superbike… me on a superbike?! Hell yeah! So I booked a flight for laguna and let my manager Shakey sort the rest 😂😂. Everything since has pretty much been living the dream!! 

I’m currently still recovering my shoulder from an end of season surgery but I hope to be back on 2 wheels shortly! Thank you all for the support and coming on this wild journey with me! 🫶🏽🫶🏽 see y’all in 24! #sendersonly #hard
